Pathogenesis of asthma

  1. Mast cell activation due to various other effectors is main factor in pathogenesis of asthma.
  2. Mast cell activation by allergen serves as an example for what happens in asthma
    1. IgE produced on first exposure binds to mast cells via Fc portion.
    2. On subsequent exposure, allergen crosslinks the bound IgE -> mast cell degranulation.

During asthma attack, the response to the trigger happens in two phases:

  1. 1Ô∏è‚É£ Early phase : mast cell degranulation -> release of mediators from mast cell

    1. Mediators include histamine, prostaglandin D2, and cysteinyl leukotrienes (LTC4, D4, and E4
    2. These directly stimulated smooth muscle -> üõëBronchoconstrictionüõë

  2. 2Ô∏è‚É£ Late phase: Sometimes, bronchoconstriction can occur hours after the early phase. This happens because of migration of various immune cells at the airways including:

    1. monocytes, dendtric cells, neutrophils <- inname immune system
    2. T lymphocytes, eosinophils and basophils <- adaptive system
    3. These also release mediators -> smooth muscle contraction ->üõë further bronchoconstriction. üõë
    4. But smooth muscle contraction isn't the only mechanism here since beta agonists don't completely reverse late phase bronchoconstriction.

Roles of each type of cell

Eosinophils Mast cell Th2 lymphocyte NKT cell Basophil
Most characteristic cell in asthma
produce lipid mediators, such as leukotrienes and platelet activating factor, Similar mediators Secrete IL 3, 4, 5, 13, GM-CSF
These cause broncho constriction Bronchoconstriction Basically support the other cells

Hepatitis B

Natural history

Infection can be acute and chronic.

Acute HBV

70% subclinical or anicteric hepatitis. ü§´
30% icteric hepatitis.

Acute hepatitis may show a serum sickness-like syndrome manifested as fever, skin rashes, arthralgia, and arthritis, which usually subsides with the onset of jaundice.

ALT and AST values up to 1000 to 2000 units/L are typically seen during the acute phase . ALT is higher than AST.
The prothrombin time is the best indicator of prognosis.

Acute hepatitis B is usually self limiting and treatment not required. üôÇ but patients with severe or persistent acute HBV may require treatment with a nucleos(t)ide analogue.

Despite the usually good prognosis of acute infection, üòÆ

  • 5% will go onto develop chronic infectionüòÆ
  • 1% will develop fulminant hepatitis -> may need liver transplant. üòÆüòÆ

Complete clearance of the virus is rare. Most people will continue to have the virus latent within the hepatocytes but kept in check by the T lymphocyte immune system even when the serologic markers show recovery.
For exam / practical purposes, serologic confirmation of recovery = actual recovery. Pathology wise, though, there is till some virus left but it's controlled by the T cells.

Coinfection

Acute HBV and HDV coinfection tends to be more severe than acute HBV infection alone and is more likely to result in fulminant hepatitis.
Some findings suggest that that HCV coinfection may interfere with the replication of HBV, leading to attenuation of liver damage

Superinfection

HDV superinfection in patients with chronic HBV infection is usually accompanied by a suppression of HBV replication due to interference mechanisms that are not well understood.
HDV superinfection in such patients has been associated with more severe liver disease and accelerated progression to cirrhosis in most studies

Chronic HBV

Manifestations range from an asymptomatic carrier state (seen in many patients) to chronic hepatitis, cirrhosis, and hepatocellular carcinoma.
HBV genotype, HBeAg status, HBV DNA and HBsAg status influence the risk of progression of disease.

Risk of progression from acute to chronic infection is inversely related with age. <- it's the main determinant of risk of chronicity.
90 % for a perinatally acquired infection
20 to 50 % if acquired from 1 - 5 years
<5 % for an adult-acquired infection

Can show extrahepatic manifestations due to immune complexes

  1. polyarteritis nodosa
  2. glomerular disease - Mostly membranous but also membranoproliferative; commonly in children. Seen as nephrotic range proteinuria. Spontaneous remission occurs in many.
  3. also aplastic anaemia
Phases of chronic HBV infection

Chronic HBV infection generally consists of 4 phases:

Characteristics of each phase:

Chronic hepatitis = Chronic necroinflammatory disease of the liver caused by persistent infection with hepatitis B virus. Chronic hepatitis B can be subdivided into HBeAg-positive and HBeAg-negative chronic hepatitis B - i.e context for the list belowl

  1. Immune tolerance: HBeAg+, high HBV DNA (usually >108 IU/mL), and persistently normal ALT
  2. HBeAg-positive chronic hepatitis -AKA immune clearance: HBeAg+, fluctuating high HBV DNA (usually >105 IU/mL), and fluctuating ALT (usually >ULN)
  3. Inactive carrier: HBeAg‚Äì, persistently low HBV DNA (usually <2000 IU/mL), and normal ALT
  4. HBeAg-negative chronic hepatitis: HBeAg‚Äì, fluctuating moderate HBV DNA (usually 103-107 IU/mL), and fluctuating ALT (usually >ULN but may be intermittently normal)

[!TIP] HBV DNA level and ALT
Fulminant hepatitis is though to occur because of immune destruction of infected hepatocytes.
In the graph above, HBV DNA level is inversely related with ALT -> probably means that hepatocytes are killed to control the HBV DNA but that simulataneously raises markers of liver damage.

The outcome of chronic HBV infection depends upon the severity of liver disease at the time HBV replication is arrested.

Outcomes if patient has chronic hepatitis B

Chronic hepatitis -> cirrhosis (15%)
Cirrhosis -> decompensated cirrhosis (20%)
Cirrhosis -> HCC (15%)

Diagnosis and serology

https://youtu.be/21eVTf0otUw
HbSAg can precede the onset of symptoms.
HBV DNA can usually be detected when HbSAg is present.
IgM -> defines acute hepatitis. Usually becomes positive with onset of symptoms.
Anti HBs - detectable during convalesence and after dissapearance of HbSAg. Shows immunity from reinfection.

Anti HBs > 10 IU => immunity confirmed + (1 - 2 months after vaccination)
HBsAg can be positive for 2 weeks following vaccinatino -> insignificant.
Anti HBsAg positivity alone => immunity following vaccination

Treatment

Goals of treatment: Clear the infection as evidenced by HBsAg and HBV levels because it reduces the risk of cirrhosis and HCC.

Main considerations:
is the presentation acute or chronic?
For acute infection - there are different criteria

  • interferon is should not be used.
    For chronic infection - there are certain criteria
  • interferon and other antiviral can be used

Treatment options

Antivirals
Interferon

Hepatitis C

  • HDV + HBV coninfection is clinically identical to acute HBV infection and usually transient and self limited. üòÄ
  • Higher risk of [[2023-SEMPaper#Acute Liver Failure|Acute liver failure]] üòï
  • Risk of chronic HDV infection is same as risk of HBV infection (because persistence of HDV infection is dependent on persistence of HBV.)
  • i.e patient has been a (diagnosed or undiagnosed) HBV carrier.
  • can present as severe acute hepatitis or exacerbation of chronic hepatitis.
  • Clinically we can't tell if it's superinfection or acute HBV but serology can distinguish the two.
  • Progression to chronic HDV occurs in all! üò£
  • Rapid progression towards cirrhosis.
  • Increased risk of hepatocellular carcinoma compared to monoinfection.
